      "content": "i see. so basically the \"instability\" is being used to justify a tougher sentence. if a judge treats his background as a personal failing rather than a systemic issue, isn't that essentially penalizing him for where he was born or raised? \n\nto push this a bit further, if Case A and Case B were exactly the same person—say, the same age, same offense, same exact employment history—but we just changed the description of his neighborhood from \"suburban\" to \"urban,\" do you think the recommended sentence would actually change in a real courtroom? like, does the location itself act as a proxy for a more dangerous character?",
